# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: plainfield-new-jersey
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/113-new-jersey-bus] The list below is sorted by division, New York terminal, the New Jersey region served, major streets, general operational details (e.g. variations, express services, short turns, operating hours), history, and garages where the routes are based.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/113-new-jersey-bus] Unless otherwise noted, routes labeled "Weekday rush hours only" run to New York during the AM rush and to New Jersey during the PM rush.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/113-new-jersey-bus] During morning rush hour, many PABT-bound routes use the Lincoln Tunnel express bus lane (XBL), a dedicated reversible lane that travels eastbound along New Jersey Route 495.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/113-new-jersey-bus] There is no west-bound XBL during the evening rush hour.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/113-new-jersey-bus] Many PABT-bound routes make stops along 30th and 31st Streets in Union City rather than running nonstop on Route 495.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/113-new-jersey-bus] Routes labeled "Serves Union City" are frequently scheduled to do this.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/113-new-jersey-bus] This label is not used for routes which make local stops in Union City anywhere other than 30th and 31st Streets.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/113-new-jersey-bus] Northern Division routes serve points in Hudson, Bergen, and Passaic counties in New Jersey, as well as in Orange County in New York.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/113-new-jersey-bus] Central Division routes go to points south of the Essex/Passaic county line, and west of the Passaic River.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/113-new-jersey-bus] These routes are assigned to the Howell Garage in Howell Twp. with some rush hour service on some lines operated by Academy Bus.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/113-new-jersey-bus] All routes operate during weekday peak hours only, except for the 137 and 139.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/113-new-jersey-bus] This list includes routes that have been renumbered, are now operated by private companies or have been discontinued.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] The **119th United States Congress** is the current meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, composed of the United States Senate and the United States House of Representatives.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] It convened on January 3, 2025, for the last 17 days of Joe Biden's presidency and continued during the first two years of Donald Trump's second presidency.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] Following the 2024 elections, the Republican Party retained its slim majority in the House of Representatives (albeit with losing two net seats to end up with a three-seat majority).
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] The Republican Party also won a three-seat majority in the Senate after winning four net seats.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] Upon Trump's second inauguration on January 20, 2025, the Republican Party has an overall federal government trifecta for the first time since the 115th Congress (2017–2019), which was in session during Trump's first term.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] The 119th Congress features the slimmest majority in the House for any party since the 72nd Congress (1931–1933), and the first openly transgender member of Congress in history, Representative Sarah McBride (D-DE).
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] It also features the fewest split Senate delegations since the passage of the Seventeenth Amendment, which established the direct election of U.S. senators.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] Despite a trifecta, the first year of the Congress saw the lowest number of House votes in a nonelection year since the 101st Congress in 1990.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] In the 2024 elections, the Republican Party retained control of the House of Representatives and gained control of the Senate, while Republican nominee Donald Trump won the presidential election, securing a second non-consecutive term.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] The results of the election were attributed to economic conditions of voters and concerns over immigration, particularly the Mexico–United States border crisis.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] The Senate flipped to a 53–47 Republican majority, and in their leadership elections, Senator John Thune of South Dakota was elected to succeed Mitch McConnell, who had been in power for 18 years.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] The House assumed a 220–215 Republican majority, among the narrowest controlling majorities in House history with the 65th Congress.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] Mike Johnson was re-elected as speaker on the first ballot after initially not receiving enough votes on the roll call, with the vote remaining open until enough members changed votes to support him.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] On January 6, a joint session convened to count the presidential Electoral College votes.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] The proceedings were peaceful, four years after the January 6 Capitol attack, in which supporters of Trump entered the Capitol and disrupted Joe Biden's certification as president.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] In response to the attack and Trump's efforts to overturn the 2020 election, Congress has passed revisions to the Electoral Count Act that prevent the vice president from altering the results and significantly raises the bar for certification objections.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] The numbers refer to their Senate classes.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] All class 1 seats were contested in the November 2024 elections.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] In this Congress, class 1 means their term commenced in the current Congress, requiring re-election in 2030; class 2 means their term ends with this Congress, requiring re-election in 2026; and class 3 means their term began in the last Congress, requiring re-election in 2028.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] All seats were filled by election in November 2024, or special elections thereafter as noted below.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] The **1870 United States census** was the ninth United States census.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] It was conducted by the Census Office from June 1, 1870, to August 23, 1871.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census was the first census to provide detailed information on the African American population, only five years after the culmination of the Civil War when slaves were granted freedom.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] The total population was 38,925,598 with a resident population of 38,558,371 individuals, a 22.6% increase from 1860.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census's population estimate was controversial, as many believed it underestimated the true population numbers, especially in New York and Pennsylvania.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] This was the first census in which all 100 largest cities recorded populations of over 10,000.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] This was also the last federal census conducted using the US Marshal Service as enumerators.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] The Census Act of 1850 established the primary machinery of the ninth census.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] The Census Office, working within the Department of the Interior, oversaw the recording and tabulation of results gathered by assistant marshals, who were hired and supervised by federal marshals.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] Two new structural changes during the 1870 census occurred: marshals had to return the completed population questionnaire to the Census Office in September, and penalties for refusing to reply to enumerator questions were extended to encompass every question on the questionnaires.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] The commonly past-used slave questionnaires were redesigned to reflect the American society after the Civil War.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] The five schedules for the 1870 census were the following: General Population, Mortality, Agriculture, Products of Industry, and Social Statistics.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] The general population saw a 22.6% increase to 38,555,983 individuals in 1870.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] Charges of an undercount, however, were brought against Francis Amasa Walker, the Superintendent of the 1870 census.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] Mortality rates in 1870, in general, decreased as a fraction of the total population by <0.1% from 1860 and by 0.1% from 1850.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] The lower death rates indicate that the standard of living increased, due to some exogenous factor, over the period of twenty years from 1850 to 1870.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] In terms of products of industry, total U.S. wealth increased by 17.3% from 1860 to 1870, to reach an assessed wealth of $14,178,986,732.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] The four largest state contributors to this wealth were New York, Massachusetts, Pennsylvania, and Ohio, in that order.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] Most of the wealth was concentrated in the developed Northeast region, as newer territories like Wyoming were beginning to develop their young economies.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census was the first of its kind to record the nativity of the American population.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] This social statistic helped determine which areas were more highly composed of immigrants than native-born Americans.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] New York City had the most foreign-born individuals, with 419,094 foreigners, who comprised 44.5% of the city's total population.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] Louis, and San Francisco also had a great population of foreigners that made up a significant fraction of their total populations.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] Therefore, a great ethnic and cultural change was witnessed from 1860 to 1870, as part of the population growth was due to immigrants moving in and a shuffling of residents across state borders.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1870 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] With especially bitter complaints coming from New York and Philadelphia claiming up to a third of the population was not counted, the President made the rare move to order a recount in those areas.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] While it was thought a large fraction of the population was not counted for being indoors in the wintry cold, newer estimates resulted in only a 2.5% increase in Philadelphia's population and a 2% increase in New York's.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] This controversy of the 1870 undercount resurfaced in 1890, when the national growth rate between 1880 and 1890 was discovered to be much lower than it was between 1870 and 1880.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] Critics then asserted that the 1870 population must have been underenumerated by over 1.2 million people to account for the discrepancy between growth rates; it was presumed that the growth rate in 1880 had to be exaggerated because of the 1870 undercount.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] Despite the fact that modern investigations have yet to quantify the exact effect of the undercount, most modern social scientists do not believe the undercount was as severe as 1890 investigators assumed.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] Today most analyzers compare the 1870 undercount to the non-response rates seen in most modern census data.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1880-united-states-census] The **1880 United States census**, conducted by the Census Office during June 1880, was the tenth United States census.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1880-united-states-census] It was the first time that women were permitted to be enumerators.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1880-united-states-census] The Superintendent of the Census was Francis Amasa Walker.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1880-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a city—New York City—recorded a population of over one million, and the first census in which the 20 most populated cities all recorded over 100,000 residents.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1880-united-states-census] Schedule 4 (Social statistics) was the responsibility of experts and special agents, rather than the enumerators.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1880-united-states-census] The majority of the data came from correspondence with officials of institutions providing care and treatment of certain members of the population.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1880-united-states-census] Experts and special agents also were employed to collect data on valuation, taxation, and indebtedness; religion and libraries; colleges, academies, and schools; newspapers and periodicals, and wages.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1880-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1880 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series, which contains microdata.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1880-united-states-census] The original census enumeration sheets were microfilmed by the Census Bureau; after which the original sheets were transferred to various state archives, libraries, or universities.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1880-united-states-census] The microfilmed census is available in rolls from the National Archives and Records Administration.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1880-united-states-census] Several organizations also host images of the microfilmed census online, along which digital indices.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1880-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1880 population census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1880-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1880-united-states-census] The 1880 census determined the resident population of the United States to be 50,189,209, an increase of 30.2 percent over the 38,555,983 persons enumerated during the 1870 census.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1880-united-states-census] The mean center of United States population for 1880 was in Boone County, Kentucky.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1880-united-states-census] The results from the census were used to determine the apportionment for the 48th, 49th, 50th, 51st, and 52nd sessions of the United States Congress.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1880-united-states-census] The processing of the 1880 census data took so long (eight years) that the Census Bureau contracted Herman Hollerith to design and build a tabulating machine to be used for the next census.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1880-united-states-census] The 1880 census also led to the discovery of the Alabama paradox.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1890-united-states-census] The **1890 United States census** was taken beginning June 2, 1890.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1890-united-states-census] The census determined the resident population of the United States to be 62,979,766, an increase of 25.5 percent over the 50,189,209 persons enumerated during the 1880 census.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1890-united-states-census] The data reported that the distribution of the population had resulted in the disappearance of the American frontier.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1890-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a majority of states recorded populations of over one million and the first in which three cities, New York City, Chicago, and Philadelphia, recorded populations of over one million.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1890-united-states-census] The census also saw Chicago rise in rank to the nation's second-most populous city, a position it would hold until Los Angeles, the 57th-most populous city as of 1890, supplanted it in 1990.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1890-united-states-census] This was the first U.S. census to use machines to tabulate the collected data.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1890-united-states-census] Most of the 1890 census materials were destroyed on January 10, 1921, when the Commerce Department building caught fire, and in the subsequent disposal of the remaining damaged records.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1890-united-states-census] The 1890 census was the first to be compiled using methods invented by Herman Hollerith and was overseen by Superintendents Robert P.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1890-united-states-census] Data was entered on a machine readable medium (punched cards) and tabulated by machine.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1890-united-states-census] Changes from the 1880 census included the larger population, the number of data items to be collected from individuals, the Census Bureau headcount, the volume of scheduled publications, and the use of Hollerith's electromechanical tabulators.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1890-united-states-census] The net effect of these changes was to reduce the time required to process the census from eight years for the 1880 census to six years for the 1890 census.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1890-united-states-census] The total population of 62,947,714, the family, or *rough*, count, was announced after only six weeks of processing (punched cards were not used for this tabulation).
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1890-united-states-census] The public reaction to this tabulation was disbelief, as it was widely believed that the "right answer" was at least 75,000,000.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1890-united-states-census] The United States census of 1890 showed a total of 248,253 Native Americans living in the United States, down from 400,764 Native Americans identified in the census of 1850.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1890-united-states-census] The 1890 census announced that the frontier region of the United States no longer existed, and that the Census Bureau would no longer track the westward migration of the U.S. population.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1890-united-states-census] In practice, however, said migration can still be tracked by plotting each succeeding census' mean center of United States population.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1890-united-states-census] By 1890, settlement in the American West had reached sufficient population density that the frontier line had disappeared.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1890-united-states-census] The original data for the 1890 census is mostly unavailable.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1890-united-states-census] The population schedules were damaged in a fire in the basement of the U.S.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1890-united-states-census] Department of Commerce building in Washington, D.C. in 1921.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1890-united-states-census] Some 25% of the materials were presumed destroyed and another 50% damaged by smoke and water, although the actual damage may have been closer to 15–25%.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1890-united-states-census] The damage to the records led to an outcry for a permanent National Archives.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1890-united-states-census] In December 1932, following standard federal record-keeping procedures, the Chief Clerk of the Bureau of the Census sent the Librarian of Congress a list of papers to be destroyed, including the original 1890 census schedules.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1890-united-states-census] The Librarian was asked by the Bureau to identify any records which should be retained for historical purposes, but the Librarian did not accept the census records.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1890-united-states-census] Congress authorized destruction of that list of records on February 21, 1933, and the surviving original 1890 census records were destroyed by government order by 1934 or 1935.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1890-united-states-census] Few sets of microdata from the 1890 census survive.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1900-united-states-census] The **1900 United States census**, conducted by the Census Office on June 1, 1900, determined the resident population of the United States to be 76,212,168, an increase of 21.01% from the 62,979,766 persons enumerated during the 1890 census.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1900-united-states-census] It was the last census to be conducted before the founding of the permanent United States Census Bureau.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1900-united-states-census] The census saw the nation's largest city, New York City, more than double in size due to the consolidation with Brooklyn, becoming in the process the first U.S. city to record a population growth of over three million — Brooklyn was previously the 4th largest city in the United States on its own.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1900-united-states-census] Oversight of the statistics was by Frederick Howard Wines and Walter F.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1900-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1900 census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1900-united-states-census] Statistician Frederick Ludwig Hoffman criticized the conduct of the census.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1900-united-states-census] The original census enumeration sheets were microfilmed by the Census Bureau in the 1940s, after which the original sheets were destroyed.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1900-united-states-census] Several organizations also host images of the microfilmed census online, and digital indices.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1900-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1900 census are freely available through IPUMS.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1900-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with electronic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/1900-united-states-census] Location of 50 largest cities by population in the United States in 1900, on a map of the modern United States.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] The area of present-day Plainfield was originally formed as Plainfield Township, a township that was created on April 5, 1847, from portions of Westfield Township, while the area was still part of Essex County.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] On March 19, 1857, Plainfield Township became part of the newly created Union County.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Plainfield was incorporated as a city by an act of the New Jersey Legislature on April 21, 1869, from portions of Plainfield Township, based on the results of a referendum held that same day.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] The city and township coexisted until March 6, 1878, when Plainfield Township was dissolved and parts were absorbed by Plainfield city, with the remainder becoming Fanwood Township (since renamed as Scotch Plains).
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] The name "Plainfield", also used in both North Plainfield and South Plainfield, is derived from a local estate or from its scenic location.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Plainfield was settled in 1684 by Quakers, and incorporated as a city in 1869.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Formerly a bedroom suburb in the New York metropolitan area, it has become the urban center of 10 closely allied municipalities, with diversified industries, including printing and the manufacture of chemicals, clothing, electronic equipment, and vehicular parts.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Among the several 18th-century buildings remaining are a Friends' meetinghouse (1788), the Martine house (1717), and the Nathaniel Drake House (1746), known as George Washington's headquarters during the Battle of Short Hills in June 1777.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Nearby Washington Rock is a prominent point of the Watchung Mountains and is reputed to be the vantage point from which Washington watched British troop movements.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] The "Queen City" moniker arose in the second half of the 19th century.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Plainfield had been developing a reputation during this period as featuring a climate that was beneficial for respiratory ailments.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] In 1886, in an effort to publicize the climate, local newspaper publisher Thomas W.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Morrison began to use the slogan "Colorado of the East" to promote Plainfield.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] George Clinton founded The Parliaments while working in a Plainfield barber shop.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Parliament-Funkadelic was inducted in the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame in 1997.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] A number of other well-known musicians are from, or have resided, in Plainfield.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] In sports history, Plainfield is the birthplace and/or home of several current and former athletes, including professionals and well-known amateurs.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Plainfield's history as a place to call home for the 19th and 20th century wealthy has led to a significant and preserved suburban architectural legacy.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] An influx of Wall Street money led to the creation of what was called Millionaires' Row after the opening of the railway in the 19th century.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] There are numerous sites, including homes, parks, and districts in the city that are listed on the National Register of Historic Places.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] While not listed, the Plainfield Armory, a prominent landmark completed in 1932, was sold by the state in 2013 as surplus property.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Plainfield's wealthy northeast corner, known as the "Sleepy Hollow" section of the city, was and still is characterized by its array of finely landscaped streets and neighborhoods with homes defined by a broad array of architectural styles, most built during the first half of the twentieth century.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] From the tree-lined neighborhoods, the lot sizes vary, but the stateliness and distinction of each house is evident, whether a stately Queen Anne mansion or a gingerbread cottage.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Most lots are nicely landscaped and semi- or fully private.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Plainfield has been home to former New Jersey governor James McGreevey.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Plainfield was affected by the Plainfield Rebellion in July 1967.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] This civil disturbance occurred in the wake of the larger Newark riots.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] A Plainfield police officer was killed, about fifty people were injured, and several hundred thousand dollars of property was damaged by looting and arson.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] The New Jersey National Guard restored order after three days of unrest.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] This civil unrest caused a massive white flight, characterized by the percentage of Black residents rising from 40% in 1970 to 60% a decade later.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Author and Plainfield native Isaiah Tremaine published *Insurrection* in 2017 as a mournful accounting of the Plainfield riots—and subsequent racial tensions at Plainfield High School—from his perspective as a Black teenager living in the city with both white and Black friends at the time.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Prior to the rebellion, Plainfield was a regional shopping and entertainment center.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Residents of nearby Union, Middlesex and Somerset counties would drive to shop and explore the business districts of Plainfield.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Other than during the holidays, peak shopping times Plainfield were Thursday nights and Saturday, when Front Street and the areas around it bustled.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Plainfield had several entertainment venues at that time.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] At the peak, there were four operating movie theaters: the Strand, the Liberty, the Paramount and the Oxford theaters.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Manufacturers of heavy goods included Chelsea Fan Corp., Mack Truck and National Starch and Chemical Corp.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Plainfield Iron and Metal maintained a large scrapyard in the West End.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] In 2025, Plainfield and surrounding communities were affected by two separate natural disasters in the span of two weeks.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] On July 3, three people were killed when severe thunderstorms swept through the area.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Heavy damage occurred when the storms brought down trees and powerlines, leaving 8,000 residents without power.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] The state of emergency was lifted on July 9.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Five days later, on July 14, flash floods killed two women when their car was swept into the Cedar Brook, designed to catch and drain all of the city's flood water.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] According to the United States Census Bureau, the city had a total area of 5.97 square miles (15.5 km2), including 5.96 square miles (15.4 km2) of land and 0.01 square miles (0.026 km2) of water (0.15%).
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Unincorporated communities, localities and place names located partially or completely within the city include Netherwood.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] The city is located in Central Jersey on the southwestern edge of Union County and is bordered by nine municipalities.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] In Union County are Scotch Plains to the north and east and Fanwood to the northeast.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] In Middlesex County, are South Plainfield and Piscataway to the south; Dunellen to the southwest and Edison to the southeast.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] In Somerset County, Green Brook Township lies to the northwest, North Plainfield lies to the north and Watchung borders to the northwest.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Plainfield is in the Raritan Valley, a line of cities in central New Jersey, and lies on the east side of the Raritan Valley along with Edison.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] The Robinson's Branch of the Rahway River additionally flows through Plainfield en route to the Robinson's Branch Reservoir.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Plainfield has a humid continental climate, characterized by brisk to cold winters and hot, muggy summers.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] The lowest temperature ever recorded was −17 °F (−27 °C) on February 9, 1934, and the highest temperature ever recorded was 106 °F (41 °C) on July 10, 1936, and August 11, 1949.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] According to the Köppen Climate Classification system, Plainfield has a humid subtropical climate, which is abbreviated as "Cfa" on climate maps.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Plainfield has seen a rapid rise in its Latino community in recent decades.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] The city's population is now majority Hispanic for the first time, as of the 2020 census.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Note: the US Census treats Hispanic/Latino as an ethnic category.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] This table excludes Latinos from the racial categories and assigns them to a separate category.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] As of the 2020 census, Plainfield had a population of 54,586.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] 27.5% of residents were under the age of 18 and 11.3% of residents were 65 years of age or older.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] For every 100 females there were 99.3 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 97.8 males age 18 and over.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] 100.0% of residents lived in urban areas, while 0.0% lived in rural areas.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] There were 16,308 households in Plainfield, of which 43.6% had children under the age of 18 living in them.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Of all households, 39.0% were married-couple households, 20.1% were households with a male householder and no spouse or partner present, and 32.3% were households with a female householder and no spouse or partner present.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] About 21.1% of all households were made up of individuals and 8.5% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] There were 17,125 housing units, of which 4.8% were vacant.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] The homeowner vacancy rate was 1.9% and the rental vacancy rate was 3.4%.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] The 2010 United States census counted 49,808 people, 15,180 households, and 10,884 families in the city.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] There were 16,621 housing units at an average density of 2,759.8 per square mile (1,065.6/km2).
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Hispanic or Latino of any race were 40.37% (20,105) of the population.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Of the 15,180 households, 35.2% had children under the age of 18; 37.9% were married couples living together; 24.1% had a female householder with no husband present and 28.3% were non-families.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Of all households, 21.3% were made up of individuals and 7.6% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] The average household size was 3.23 and the average family size was 3.60.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] For every 100 females, the population had 101.3 males.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] For every 100 females ages 18 and older there were 100.4 males.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] The Census Bureau's 2006–2010 American Community Survey showed that (in 2010 inflation-adjusted dollars) median household income was $52,056 (with a margin of error of +/− $3,048) and the median family income was $58,942 (+/− $4,261).
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] About 12.2% of families and 16.8% of the population were below the poverty line, including 23.5% of those under age 18 and 16.0% of those age 65 or over.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] As of the 2000 United States census of 2000, there were 47,829 people, 15,137 households, and 10,898 families residing in the city.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] The population density was 7,921.7 people per square mile (3,058.6 people/km2).
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] There were 16,180 housing units at an average density of 2,679.8 per square mile (1,034.7/km2).
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] The racial makeup of the city was 21.45% White, 61.78% African American, 0.41% Native American, 0.93% Asian, 0.10% Pacific Islander, 10.78% from other races, and 4.55% from two or more races.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Hispanic or Latino of any race were 25.16% of the population.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] There were 15,137 households, out of which 35.5% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 39.3% were married couples living together, 24.5% had a female householder with no husband present, and 28.0% were non-families.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] 21.1% of all households were made up of individuals, and 7.4% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] The average household size was 3.10 and the average family size was 3.49.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] In the city the population was spread out, with 27.5% under the age of 18, 10.2% from 18 to 24, 32.6% from 25 to 44, 20.5% from 45 to 64, and 9.2% who were 65 years of age or older.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] For every 100 females, there were 95.7 males.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 92.2 males.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] The median income for a household in the city was $46,683, and the median income for a family was $50,774.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Males had a median income of $33,460 versus $30,408 for females.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] The per capita income for the city was $19,052.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] About 12.2% of families and 15.9% of the population were below the poverty line, including 21.3% of those under age 18 and 12.6% of those age 65 or over.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Portions of Plainfield are part of an Urban Enterprise Zone.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] The city was selected in 1983 as one of the initial group of 10 zones chosen to participate in the program.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] In addition to other benefits to encourage employment within the Zone, shoppers can take advantage of a reduced 3.3125% sales tax rate (half of the 6+5⁄8% rate charged statewide) at eligible merchants.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Established in January 1986, the city's Urban Enterprise Zone status expires in December 2023.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] The UEZ program in Plainfield and four other original UEZ cities had been allowed to lapse as of January 1, 2017, after Governor Chris Christie, who called the program an "abject failure", vetoed a compromise bill that would have extended the status for two years.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] In May 2018, Governor Phil Murphy signed a law that reinstated the program in these five cities and extended the expiration date in other zones.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Downtown Plainfield has two historic commercial districts: the North Avenue Commercial District and the Plainfield Civic District.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Both are on the National Register of Historic Places.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Events such as the Christmas Tree Lighting, the Queen City 5k, Fire Safety Fair, and Mayor's Wellness Walk take place in the Downtown each year.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] The restoration of large 19th century-era Plainfield estates to their original glory, such as the Craig Marsh home, has been featured in various home design magazine coverage.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Part of the West End is known to locals as Soulville.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Mount Olive Baptist Church has been serving the West End as a community of faith since 1870.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] It is considered Plainfield's first Black church.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] As the Black community grew, other congregations branched off from Mount Olive.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Calvary Baptist Church began in 1897 among a group of Black congregants from Mount Olive, and celebrated its 120th anniversary in 2017 with a series of events.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Nearby, Shiloh Baptist Church was founded in 1908, also by Mount Olive congregants, and offers many faith-based events to the community, including its Jazz for Jesus program.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] The West End has been eyed recently for redevelopment.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] The White Star, a diner in the West End on West Front Street near Green Brook Park, has been an area meeting spot and landmark for over half a century.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] The West End has grown more Latino in recent years.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] As of the 2020 census, 51% of all people living in Plainfield were of Hispanic origin.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] In his book *Insurrection*, Isaiah Tremaine, a Black Plainfield native, credits the influx of Latinos for breathing new life and energy into a city hurting from racism and racial strife in the 1970s.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] In 2022, the city of Plainfield renamed a section of Plainfield Avenue, from its intersection with Front Street to its intersection with West Fifth Street, as "Parliament Funkadelic Way" in honor of its musical history.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] A sizable and diverse LGBTQ+ community contributes to the long-time perception of Plainfield as a stronghold of gay life and gay community in the suburbs of New Jersey.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Plainfield has one of the highest percentage of same-sex householders in the state of New Jersey.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] The First Unitarian Society of Plainfield, the oldest such congregation in the United States, is certified as LGBTQ welcoming.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] In 1986, *The New York Times* reported on what was termed at the time as the "growing homosexual population in Plainfield" drawn to the stock of aging Victorian, Tudor and colonial homes, and featured interviews with various gay men who lived in Plainfield and worked in Manhattan.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] One of the Queen City's elected leaders, former Councilwoman Rebecca Williams (who now represents all of Union County a county commissioner), is openly lesbian.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] In 2017, as Council President, Williams organized and hosted the city's first-ever Pride flag-raising during Pride Month.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] In 2015, an openly gay Plainfield Republican ran for state Assemblyman.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Plainfield has been home to openly gay former New Jersey governor James McGreevey and his longtime partner, an Australian-American business executive.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Plainfield is also at the center of gay life in Union County, which hosts LGBTQ family events and opened the state's first county-wide office of LGBTQ services in 2018.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Tëmike Park is an LGBTQ+ welcoming space in Cedar Brook Park in Plainfield between Stelle Avenue and Randolph Road.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] It is named for a Lenape-language expression of welcome.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Remaining multi-community newspapers include the *Courier News*, a daily newspaper based in Bridgewater Township, and *The Star-Ledger* based in Newark.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] The *Courier News* is a consolidation of *The Evening News* (founded in 1884), the *Plainfield Daily Press* (founded in 1887) and the *Plainfield Courier* (founded in 1891).
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] The paper was based in the city and called the *Plainfield Courier News* until 1972, when it moved westward to Bridgewater.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] As of 2017, local media in New Jersey has undergone dramatic shrinkage.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Plainfield Plaintalker (2005–2010) and Plaintalker II (2010–2017) were two local blogs published by longtime local reporter Bernice Paglia.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] From 1961 to 1997, Plainfield was home to WERA at 1590 on the AM dial with studios at 120 West 7th Street.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Plainfield is governed under a special charter granted by the New Jersey Legislature.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] The city is one of 11 (of the 564) municipalities statewide governed under a special charter.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] The governing body is comprised of a mayor and a seven-member city council, all of whom serve four-year terms in office.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] The city is divided into four wards, with one ward seat up for election each year.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] There are three at-large seats: one from the First and Fourth Wards; one from the Second and Third Wards; and one from the city as a whole.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] The three at-large seats and mayoral seat operate in a four-year cycle, with one seat up for election each year.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] As of 2026, the Mayor of the City of Plainfield is Democrat Adrian O.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Mapp, whose term of office ends December 31, 2029.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Members of the Plainfield City Council are Council President Julienne Cherry (At Large Wards 1 and 4; D, 2027), Council Vice President Steve G.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Hockaday (At Large All Wards; D, 2028), Terri Briggs-Jones (Ward 4; D, 2029), Robert K.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Graham (Ward 1; D, 2026), Charles McRae (Ward 3; D, 2028), Darcella Sessomes (Ward 2; D, 2027) and Richard Wyatt (At Large Wards 2 and 3; D, 2026).
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Plainfield is located in the 12th Congressional District and is part of New Jersey's 22nd state legislative district.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] For the 119th United States Congress, New Jersey's 12th congressional district is represented by Bonnie Watson Coleman (D, Ewing Township).
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] New Jersey is represented in the United States Senate by Democrats Cory Booker (Newark, term ends 2027) and Andy Kim (Moorestown, term ends 2031).
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] For the 2026–2027 session, the 22nd legislative district of the New Jersey Legislature is represented in the State Senate by Nicholas Scutari (D, Linden) and in the General Assembly by Linda S.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Union County is governed by a Board of County Commissioners, whose nine members are elected at-large to three-year terms of office on a staggered basis with three seats coming up for election each year, with an appointed County Manager overseeing the day-to-day operations of the county.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] At an annual reorganization meeting held in the beginning of January, the board selects a Chair and Vice Chair from among its members.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Vice Chair Rebecca Williams (D, Plainfield, 2028), Chairman Joesph Bodek (D, Linden, 2026), James E.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] (D, Rahway, 2027), Michele Delisfort (D, Union Township, 2026), Lourdes M.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Leon (D, Elizabeth, 2026), Alexander Mirabella (D, Fanwood, 2027) Kimberly Palmieri-Mouded (D, Westfield, 2027).
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Constitutional officers elected on a countywide basis are: Clerk Joanne Rajoppi (D, Union Township, 2030), Sheriff Peter Corvelli (D, Kenilworth, 2026) and Surrogate Christopher E.
