[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] The Plainfield Public School District serves students in kindergarten through twelfth grade.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] The district is one of 31 former Abbott districts statewide that were established pursuant to the decision by the New Jersey Supreme Court in *Abbott v.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Burke* which are now referred to as "SDA Districts" based on the requirement for the state to cover all costs for school building and renovation projects in these districts under the supervision of the New Jersey Schools Development Authority.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] As of the 2022–23 school year, the district, comprised of 14 schools, had an enrollment of 10,097 students and 628.7 classroom teachers (on an FTE basis), for a student–teacher ratio of 16.1:1.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Schools in the district (with 2022–23 enrollment data from the National Center for Education Statistics) are DeWitt D.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Barlow Elementary School (417 students; in grades K–5), Charles and Anna Booker Elementary School (NA; PreK–5), Cedarbrook K-8 Center (623; K–8), Clinton Elementary School (413; K–5), Frederic W.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Cook Elementary School (389; K–5), Emerson Community School (509; K–5), Evergreen Elementary School (602; K–5), Jefferson Elementary School (441; K–5), Charles H.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Stillman Elementary School (354; K–5), Washington Community School (649; K–5), Frank J.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Hubbard Middle School (775; 6–8), Maxson Middle School (818; 6–8), Pinnacle Academy High School (90; 9–12), Plainfield Academy for the Arts and Advanced Studies (356; 7–12) and Plainfield High School (1,925; 9–12).
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] The district's main high school was the 318th-ranked public high school in New Jersey out of 339 schools statewide in *New Jersey Monthly* magazine's September 2014 cover story on the state's "Top Public High Schools", using a new ranking methodology.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] The school had been ranked 280th in the state of 328 schools in 2012, after being ranked 307th in 2010 out of 322 schools listed.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] The school was removed in 2009 from the list of persistently dangerous schools in New Jersey.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Plainfield is also home to New Jersey's first high school focused on sustainability, the Barack Obama Green Charter High School.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Established in 1984, Koinonia Academy moved to Plainfield in 1997, where it serves students in Pre-K through twelfth grades and operates under the auspices of the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Newark.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Union College, a community college headquartered in nearby Cranford, maintains a campus in downtown Plainfield.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] As of May 2010, the city had a total of 101.79 miles (163.82 km) of roadways, of which 87.58 miles (140.95 km) were maintained by the municipality, 14.21 miles (22.87 km) by Union County.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Plainfield is one of the few large suburban cities in central New Jersey to have no federal highway within it.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] The only major thoroughfare through Plainfield is Route 28, connecting Somerville with Elizabeth and New Jersey Route 27.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Route 22, a mecca for highway shopping and dining, is accessible from Plainfield through North Plainfield, Dunellen and Fanwood.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] In the early 1960s, Interstate highways were completed near, but not through Plainfield.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Interstate 287 is accessible through South Plainfield and Piscataway, while Interstate 78 is accessible through Watchung / Warren Township and neighboring communities.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] The busiest connecting thoroughfares are Park Avenue (north-south), traversing from U.S.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] 22 to and into South Plainfield and Edison; Front Street (east-west), connecting Scotch Plains with Dunellen; South Avenue and 7th Street, both of which parallel Front Street, connecting Scotch Plains/Fanwood with Piscataway, South Plainfield and the Middlesex County border.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Plainfield has two NJ Transit rail stations on the Raritan Valley Line, formerly the mainline of the Central Railroad of New Jersey.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] The main Plainfield station is in the downtown and a second, smaller Netherwood station is in the Netherwood section, east of downtown and within a mile of the Fanwood border.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] A third station, located in the west end of town, was closed long ago.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] The New Brunswick train station is approximately 15 minutes away.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] The Central Railroad of New Jersey first offered service to Plainfield in 1839.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] At the height of popularity, the Plainfield "Jersey Central" train station, with its main station building constructed in 1902, was a hub for commuting to Newark and New York.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] (The Central Railroad of New Jersey terminal was in Jersey City, where ferries would take the rail passengers to New York City.) The station was located near the main post office and downtown stores.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] The station was serviced by the now defunct Railway Express postal carrier company.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] NJ Transit provides bus service on the 113 and 114 to and from the Port Authority Bus Terminal in Midtown Manhattan; the 59, 65 and 66 (limited) to Newark; and local service on the 819 and 822 routes.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] In years past, Plainfield was serviced by the Somerset Bus Company with service from Union County to Essex and New York City, the Public Service Bus Company with similar service and Plainfield Transit, providing local service.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Newark Liberty International Airport is approximately 30 minutes away.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] A proposed PATH train extension to Plainfield in the 1970s, with stops at the airport and at Elizabeth, was canceled in 1976.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Solaris Health System, the nonprofit company that owns Muhlenberg Regional Medical Center, asked for permission to close the hospital.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] This request has been opposed by People's Organization for Progress, an advocacy group based in Newark, New Jersey.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] The closing has been attributed to the large number of uninsured patients served by the hospital.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Neighborhood Health Services Corporation (NHSC) is a 501(c)(3) nonprofit community health center serving the greater Plainfield and Elizabeth communities.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] NHSC has been designated a Federally Qualified Health Center (FQHC) by the U.S.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Department of Health & Human Service's Bureau of Primary Health.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] NHSC's 340B Drug Pricing Program, in partnership with Drug Mart Pharmacy of South Plainfield, New Jersey, provides eligible patients access to outpatient drugs at significantly reduced prices.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] At the height of popularity in the 1950s through the 1970s, Plainfield was a hub for medical practices.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Park Avenue was lined with doctors and medical offices and was nicknamed "Doctors Row".
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] Plainfield Teachers College was a mythical institution created as a hoax by two college football fans in 1941.
[src:plainfield-new-jersey/plainfield-new-jersey-p01] The phony college's equally nonexistent football team had its scores carried by major newspapers including *The New York Times* before the hoax was discovered.
